<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Notifications</strong> is the <strong>notification domain home</strong> &mdash; the
    orchestration concern (which surface a notification targets, grouping, dedup, badging) plus the
    <strong>closed-app push-delivery protocol</strong>. It was ratified across two decisions:
    <a href="/backlog/009-gap-13-webpermissions-project/">#009</a> minted the domain home (render surfaces +
    orchestration + a <code>notification-marker</code> family), and
    <a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a> settled the
    transport home <em>by purpose</em>: <strong>push lives here</strong>; the open-app realtime family
    (WebSocket/SSE/WebTransport) gets its own home, because the two are non-fungible &mdash; a hard
    capability cliff separates closed-app push from a live socket.
  </p>
  <p>
    Push delivery is a <strong>Protocol, not an intent</strong>. Subscription + VAPID + provider
    orchestration is async, server-authoritative, and swappable &mdash; the same shape as a guard provider,
    never UX vocabulary. The native anchor is the <strong>Web Push API</strong> (a service-worker
    <code>PushSubscription</code> against a push service), and a <code>CustomPushProvider</code> seam lets a
    multi-channel hub (web-push, FCM, OneSignal, Novu) plug in behind one contract. A consuming project sees
    the <em>render</em> intents, never the transport.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not feedback, not background-task, not the realtime transports</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <code>feedback</code> is the <em>in-app toast</em> tier (gone when the tab closes); Web Notifications
      owns the <strong>OS-surfaced, server-deliverable</strong> notification that survives tab close. The
      <code>background-task</code> intent owns <em>in-session</em> persistence, a different lifecycle. And
      push is <strong>closed-app only</strong>: the open-app realtime family (WebSocket / SSE /
      WebTransport / long-poll) is a separate transport home (<a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a>),
      not this protocol &mdash; you don't fall back from a live socket to a closed-app push.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

