<section id="composition" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Render intents (Web Intents)</strong> &mdash; <code>system-notification</code> (the OS
      surface) and <code>notification-marker</code> (the in-app unread/badge) publish standalone and are
      coordinated by this domain; a consumer composes them.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/intents/permission/">Permissions intent</a></strong> &mdash; the cross-cutting <code>granted/denied/prompt</code>
      tri-state (camera/geolocation/clipboard too) gates the "enable notifications" affordance; not owned
      here.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webreporting/">Web Reporting</a> / <a href="/projects/webaudit/">Web
      Audit</a></strong> &mdash; a <code>DeliveryReceipt</code> is a report source / an audit event.</li>
    <li><strong>Realtime transport home (<a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a>)</strong>
      &mdash; the sibling open-app delivery family; the by-purpose split keeps push and realtime in
      distinct homes.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="status" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Notifications is in <strong>concept</strong> phase; the push-delivery protocol's contract is
    specified here. The domain home was ratified in
    <a href="/backlog/009-gap-13-webpermissions-project/">#009</a> (Fork D) and the by-purpose transport
    split in <a href="/backlog/455-server-to-client-delivery-transport-home-by-purpose-vs-by-me/">#455</a>
    (Fork 1). Follow-ons: author the <code>system-notification</code> and <code>notification-marker</code>
    render intents in Web Intents, and the open-app <code>webrealtime</code> transport home (#455 Fork 2).
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does the orchestration config own surface-routing policy (push vs marker vs badge) declaratively, or
      is routing a consumer decision the domain only provides primitives for?</li>
    <li>Is the dedup/collapse key part of the protocol payload (so providers honour it uniformly) or an
      orchestration-layer concern above the transport?</li>
    <li>Does a <code>DeliveryReceipt</code> standardize a status vocabulary, or stay an open string the
      provider supplies (mirroring the Report/Decision open-vocabulary pattern)?</li>
  </ul>
</section>
